  "doc_id": "35913",
  "text": "NMR studies have confirmed that the 3-D structure of the cC monomer is similar to that described for the monomeric part of HCC (Ekiel et al., 1997) , with the structural similarity being 62.5%. In addition, the two proteins also share similar physicochemical properties [CITATION_1] . Nevertheless, the heat stability of cC is much higher than that of HCC [CITATION_2] . The main difference between the two structures is the presence/absence of α-helix2 in AS (Fig. 1A) . In our previous work, we have demonstrated that AS plays an important role in amyloidogenic cystatin dimerization between two cystatin monomers [CITATION_3] . Alignment of HCC and cC showed that E82 of cC corresponds to P84 of HCC (Fig. 1B) . HCC does 4 not contain α-helix2 in the AS region, but P84 is located in the center of the AS region, Proline is known to act as a structural disruptor if it is present in the middle of a regular secondary structure element such as helices and -sheets [CITATION_4] . We speculated that the P84 may disrupt the α-helix2 in HCC so that the HCC monomer is less stable than that of cC, and this could eventually lead to the dimerization and further fibrillization of HCC. To clearly demonstrate this hypothesis, we constructed an AS truncated mutant (ΔW) in which residues 77-85 of α-helix2 were deleted. Moreover, the disulfide bond formed between Cys71-Cys81 might be a key factor in initiating the unfolding of cC (Cys73-Cys83 in HCC) [CITATION_5] . To minimize the effect induced by the loss of the Cys71-Cys81 disulfide bond and to investigate the importance of the proline residue in HCC, a E82P mutant of cC was employed in the study.",
